{{Use American English|date=February 2018}} {{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Toby Barbara Orenstein | image = | caption = Orenstein at a Starfish Sponsor Program event in [[Columbia, Maryland]], May 2017 | birth_name = {{nowrap|Toby Barbara Press}} | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1937|05|23|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Bronx]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] {{nowrap|United States}} | residence = [[Columbia, Maryland]] | alma_mater = [[Columbia University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]])}} | occupation = {{Hlist|Director|Educator|Business Owner}} | organization = [[Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts]], [[Young Columbians]], [[Toby's Dinner Theatre]] | spouse = Hal Orenstein | parents = Sam Press, Mildred Press | honors = [[Maryland Women's Hall of Fame]], [[Tony Honors for Excellence in Theatre]] }} '''Toby Barbara Orenstein''' née '''Press''' (born May 23, 1937) is an American theatrical director, producer, and educator. She has two honorable mentions for the [[Tony Honors for Excellence in Theatre]].<ref name=Tony>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tonyawards.com/en_US/nominees/education_award.html|title=The Tony Awards and Carnegie Mellon University Announce the Winner of the 2017 Excellence in Theatre Education Award|website=TonyAwards.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-16}}</ref> Orenstein was inducted into the [[Maryland Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2008.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://msa.maryland.gov/megafile/msa/speccol/sc3500/sc3520/014900/014919/html/14919bio.html|title=Toby Barbara Orenstein, Maryland Women's Hall of Fame|last=|first=|date=2007|website=msa.maryland.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref> Selected by [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] for her federal education project in the [[Harlem]], Orenstein taught [[Dramaturgy]] to students in a local public school in the late 1950s.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":5">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1002120080|title=COLUMBIA AT 50 : a memoir of a city|first=Len|last=Lazarick|date=2017|publisher=BOOKLOCKER COM|isbn=1634924541|location=[S.l.]|oclc=1002120080}}</ref> In 1972, at the request of pioneering businessman and [[Philanthropy|philanthropist]] [[James Rouse]], Orenstein founded the non-profit [[Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts]] through which, the nationally acclaimed theatre troupe the [[Young Columbians]] was created for the [[United States Bicentennial]].<ref name=":0" /> Later, Orenstein established the award-winning [[Toby's Dinner Theatre]] in 1975.<ref name=":5" /> Her commitment to the [[performing arts]] is considered legendary.<ref name=":6">{{Cite web|url=http://msa.maryland.gov/msa/educ/exhibits/womenshall/html/orenstein.html|title=Toby Barbara Orenstein, Maryland Women's Hall of Fame|last=Maryland State Archives|first=|date=2008|website=msa.maryland.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-10-16}}
</ref>
Alongside her work in theatre, Orenstein is a community and social activist, and is the president of the board of directors for the [[Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cctarts.org/board-of-directors-2/|title=Board of Directors - Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts|work=Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts|access-date=2017-10-16|language=en-US}}</ref> She raises funds for scholarships and community programs including over ten years of producing Labor of Love to raise money for the AIDS Alliance of [[Howard County, Maryland|Howard County]].<ref name=":6" /> Orenstein has also chaired and directed the Howard County Arts Gala for the Arts Council (3 years), participated in the events for the [[Ben Carson|Carson Scholars Fund]], and directed and produced plays for [[United Service Organizations]] and the [[United States Armed Forces]] stationed overseas.<ref name=":6" /> In 2014, Orenstein was honored with the Leadership Award for Accessibility by the Howard County Commission on Disabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mdtheatreguide.com/2017/02/news-announcement-of-winners-of-md-theatre-guides-best-of-2016-readers-choice-awards/|title=Announcement of WINNERS of MD Theatre Guide’s Best of 2016 Readers’ Choice Awards|last=Beachy|first=Mark|date=2017-02-12|website=mdtheatreguide.com|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-10-16}}</ref>
==Early life== Orenstein was born [[The Bronx]], [[New York City]], to Mildred and Sam Press.<ref name="Shird">{{Cite web|url=http://msa.maryland.gov/megafile/msa/speccol/sc3500/sc3520/014900/014919/html/14919bio.html|title=Toby Barbara Orenstein|last=Shird|first=Shannon|date=2008|website=Maryland State Archives|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref> As a child, Orenstein had an innate proclivity towards drama leading to her first role was as a pilgrim in a kindergarten play.<ref name="Shird" /> This interest in drama continued through [[Primary school]] where she directed shows in school and on the playground with her classmates.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Lives in Art: Sixteen Women Who Changed Theatre in Baltimore|last=Loeschke|first=Maravene|publisher=|year=2001|isbn=|location=|pages=45}}</ref>
Orenstein successfully auditioned for the selective [[High School of Performing Arts]] in New York City. Onlookers of the audition described her delivery of a [[monologue]] as coming from "the gut."<ref name="Shird" /> After the initial excitement of the acceptance, Orenstein eventually developed a dislike of the school's "lacking support system."<ref name="Shird" /> Orenstein says of her time at the Performing Arts school, “[It was] cut-throat competitive, not at all a nurturing environment.”<ref name="Shird" /> Subsequently, Orenstein transferred to a local Bronx high school in the middle of her [[Junior (education)|junior year]] where she where she won best actress and directed the senior show.<ref name="Shird" />
==Career== Upon graduation with a B.F.A. in theatre and a minor in education from [[Columbia University]],<ref name=":0" /> Orenstein was selected as one of twelve teachers for [[Eleanor Roosevelt]]'s federal education project in [[Harlem]], New York called the All Day Neighborhood School Project.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://hermindmagazine.com/wp/stage-mother/|title=Stage Mother|date=2017-03-11|work=HerMind|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tobysdinnertheatre.com/about-us/meet-toby/|title=Meet Toby|work=Toby's Dinner Theatre|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US}}</ref> In 1972, at the request of [[James Rouse]],<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://cctarts.org/|title=Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts|website=Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/howard/columbia/ph-ho-cf-ccta-0622-20170622-story.html|title=Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts celebrates 45 years with reunion, free performance|last=Kelemen|first=Carolyn|work=Columbia Flier|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US}}</ref> Orenstein became the founder and director of the [[Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts]] (CCTA),<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=http://tobysdinnertheatre.com/about-us/meet-toby/|title=About Us|last=|first=|date=|work=Toby's Dinner Theatre|access-date=2017-10-11|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> a non-profit 501(c)(3) organization that is funded, in part, by the [[National Endowment for the Arts]], the [https://www.msac.org/ Maryland State Arts Council], and the [https://www.hocoarts.org/ Howard County Arts Council].<ref name=":2" /> In 1975, she created the [[Young Columbians]], a dynamic performance troupe of young people aged 8–21.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":4" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cctarts.org/program/young-columbians/|title=The Young Columbians|last=|first=|date=|work=Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts|access-date=2017-10-11|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> Its graduates include several Broadway actors and, most notably, former [[Howard County, Maryland|Howard County]] resident [[Edward Norton]], an acclaimed actor, activist and [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominee.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/19/movies/he-s-hot-but-cool-to-lure-of-fame.html|title=He's Hot But Cool To Lure Of Fame|last=Hoban|first=Phoebe|date=1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Other notable alumni of the Young Columbians include [[Steve Blanchard]], [[Caroline Bowman]], [[Grace Davina]], and [[Ric Ryder]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/bs-exho-columbia-center-for-theatrical-arts-marks-40-years-of-inspiring-young-talent-20120404-story.html|title=Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts marks 40 years of inspiring young talent|last=Nitkin|first=Karen|work=Baltimore Sun|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":3" /> Performance venues include the [[White House]], [[Wolf Trap National Park for the Performing Arts|Wolf Trap]], [[Walt Disney World]], [[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts|The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts,]] [[Merriweather Post Pavilion]], [[The Fillmore]], [[Lake Kittamaqundi]], [[The Ellipse]], [[House of the Temple]], the [[Washington D.C. Temple]], and others. Since 1979, Orenstein is also the Artistic Director and owner of [[Toby's Dinner Theatre]] in [[Columbia, Maryland]].<ref name=":4" />
== Personal life == Orenstein is married to [[economist]] Harold (Hal) Orenstein. Together they have two children: a son, Jeffery (born 1961), and a daughter, Mindy (born 1963). They reside in [[Columbia, Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://cctarts.org/our-founder/|title=Our Founder: Toby Orenstein - Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts|work=Columbia Center for Theatrical Arts|access-date=2017-10-20|language=en-US}}</ref>
== Education and awards ==
=== Education === * [[High School of Performing Arts]] (first 2.5 years){{refn|group=notes|In 1961, The [[High School of Performing Arts]] and [[The High School of Music & Art]] merged into [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School]].}} * [[The Bronx|Bronx]] (area) High School * [[State University of New York at Cortland|Cortland State Teachers’ College]] (first year){{refn|group=notes|Cortland State Teachers' College was later renamed to [[State University of New York at Cortland]].}} * B.F.A. in Theatre with a minor in education from [[Columbia University]]
=== Awards === * 1985: Voted Columbian of the Year by ''Columbia Magazine'' * 1990: Howie Award for outstanding contributions to the Arts in Howard County * 1996: Helen Hayes Award nomination for Outstanding Director of a Musical * 1996: Business Volunteer of the Year, [[Howard County, Maryland|Howard County]] * 1996-99: Voted Best of [[Baltimore]] by ''[[Baltimore (magazine)|Baltimore Magazine]]'' for Toby’s Dinner Theatre * 1998: Outstanding Women by the [[Maryland State Department of Education]] for creativity and enriching the lives of people in Maryland<ref name=":0" /> * 1997: [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] Alliance Community Recognition Award for 10 years of service, support and guidance * 2001: Featured in the book: ''Lives in Arts: Sixteen Women Who Changed Theatre in Baltimore'' * 2001: Selected Honorary Chair for Howard County Arts Gala * 2002: Named to Howard County Women’s Hall of Fame * 2003: [[Helen Hayes Award]] for Outstanding Direction of a Musical, ''[[Jekyll & Hyde (musical)|Jekyll & Hyde]]''; Maryland’s Top 100 Women, ''The Daily Record'' * 2004: [[National Education Association]] Summer Assessment Grant * 2005: Outstanding Service to Educational Theatre, Maryland Theatre Association * 2007: Marylander of Distinction, ''Maryland Life Magazine'' * 2008: Maryland Women’s Hall of Fame, Maryland Commission for Women<ref name=":0" /> * 2011: Exemplar Award: ACE Hall of Fame, Howard County Chamber of Commerce<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.howardchamber.com/chamber_information/ace_hall_of_fame.aspx|title=ACE Hall of Fame|publisher=Howard County Chamber of Commerce|language=en|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref> * 2012: Sue Hess Maryland Arts Advocate of the Year Award, [http://mdarts.org/ Maryland Citizens for the Arts]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/howard/bs-ho-neighbors-toby-orenstein-award-0205-20120201-story.html|title=Toby's founder Orenstein wins award for community work|first=Janene|last=Holzberg|work=Howard County Times|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US}}</ref> * 2015: Audrey Robbins Humanitarian Employee of the Year from the Association of Community Services of Howard County<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acshoco.org/AudreyRobbinsHumanitarianAwards|title=Association of Community Services - Audrey Robbins Humanitarian Awards History|website=www.acshoco.org|language=en|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref> * 2015: Sonya Award from the [http://carsonscholars.org/ Carson Scholars fund] and presented by [[Ben Carson]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://carsonscholars.org/blog/2015-maryland-awards-banquet/|title=2015 Maryland Awards Banquet|date=2015-05-07|work=Carson Scholars Fund|access-date=2017-10-11|language=en-US}}</ref> * 2016: Person of the Year: Readers' Choice Awards, Maryland Theatre Guide<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mdtheatreguide.com/2017/02/news-announcement-of-winners-of-md-theatre-guides-best-of-2016-readers-choice-awards/|title=News: Announcement of WINNERS of MD Theatre Guide’s Best of 2016 Readers’ Choice Awards|publisher=Maryland Theatre Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref> * 2016: Helen Production Award nomination with [[Lawrence B. Munsey]] for Outstanding Director of a Musical, ''[[Ragtime (musical)|Ragtime, The Musical]]''. * 2016: Helen Production Award nomination for Outstanding Ensemble in a Musical, ''Ragtime, The Musical''. * 2017: [[Tony Honors for Excellence in Theatre]] Honorable Mention presented by [[Carnegie Mellon University]]<ref name=Tony />
